.1.1 Online version at the Perseus Digital Library].\n* [[Ovid]], ''[[Amores (Ovid)|Amores]]'', Christopher Marlowe, Ed. [http://www.perseus.tufts.edu/hopper/text?doc=Perseus%3Atext%3A1999.03.0016%3Abook%3D1%3Apoem%3D1 Online version at the Perseus Digital Library].\n* [[Ovid]]. ''[[Metamorphoses]], Volume II: Books 9-15''. Translated by Frank Justus Miller. Revised by G. P. Goold. [[Loeb Classical Library]] No. 43. Cambridge, Massachusetts: [[Harvard University Press]], 1984, first published 1916. {{ISBN|978-0-674-99047-0}}. [https://www.loebclassics.com/view/LCL043/1916/volume.xml Online version at Harvard University Press].\n* [[Pausanias (geographer)|Pausanias]], ''Pausanias Description of Greece with an English Translation by W.H.S. Jones, Litt.D., and H.A. Ormerod, M.A., in 4 Volumes.'' Cambridge, Massachusetts, Harvard University Press; London, William Heinemann Ltd. 1918. [http://www.perseus.tufts.edu/hopper/text?doc=Paus.+1.1.1 Online version at the Perseus Digital Library].\n* [[Plato]], ''[[Phaedrus (dialogue)|Phaedrus]]'' in ''Plato in Twelve Volumes'', Vol. 9 translated by Harold N. Fowler, Cambridge, Massachusetts, [[Harvard University Press]]; London, William Heinemann Ltd. 1925. [http://data.perseus.org/texts/urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0059.tlg012.perseus-eng1 Online version at the Perseus Digital Library].\n* [[Maurus Servius Honoratus|Servius]], ''Commentary on the Georgics of Vergil'', Georgius Thilo, Ed. 1881. [http://www.perseus.tufts.edu/hopper/text?doc=Perseus%3Atext%3A2007.01.0092%3Abook%3D1%3Acommline%3Dpr Online version at the Perseus Digital Library (Latin)].\n* [[William Smith (lexicographer)|Smith, William]]; ''[[Dictionary of Greek and Roman Biography and Mythology]]'', London (1873). [http://www.perseus.tufts.edu/hopper/text?doc=Perseus%3atext%3a1999.04.0104 Online version at the Perseus Digital Library].\n* [[Sophocles]], ''[[The Women of Trachis|The Trachiniae]]'' in  ''The Trachiniae of Sophocles. Edited with introduction and notes by Sir Richard Jebb'', [[Richard Claverhouse Jebb|Sir Richard Jebb]], Cambridge, [[Cambridge University Press]], 1898. [http://data.perseus.org/texts/urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0011.tlg001.perseus-eng1 Online version at the Perseus Digital Library].\n* [[Strabo]], [[Geographica|''Geography'']], translated by Horace Leonard Jones; Cambridge, Massachusetts: Harvard University Press; London: William Heinemann, Ltd. (1924). [http://penelope.uchicago.edu/Thayer/E/Roman/Texts/Strabo/home.html LacusCurtis], [http://www.perseus.tufts.edu/hopper/text?doc=Perseus%3Atext%3A1999.01.0198%3Abook%3D6%3Achapter%3D1%3Asection%3D1 Online version at the Perseus Digital Library, Books 6&ndash;14]\n* [[Thucydides]], ''Thucydides translated into English; with introduction, marginal analysis, notes, and indices. Volume 1.'', Benjamin Jowett. translator. Oxford. Clarendon Press. 1881. [http://www.perseus.tufts.edu/hopper/text?doc=Perseus%3atext%3a1999.04.0105 Online version at the Perseus Digital Library].\n* Tripp, Edward, ''Crowell's Handbook of Classical Mythology'', Thomas Y. Crowell Co; First edition (June 1970). {{ISBN|069022608X}}.\n* [[Martin Litchfield West|West, M. L.]] (2003), ''Greek Epic Fragments: From the Seventh to the Fifth Centuries BC'', edited and translated by Martin L. West, [[Loeb Classical Library]] No. 497, Cambridge, Massachusetts, [[Harvard University Press]], 2003.  {{ISBN|978-0-674-99605-2}}. [http://www.loebclassics.com/view/LCL497/2003/volume.xml Online version at Harvard University Press].\n\n==External links==\n* {{Cite EB1911|wstitle=Achelous |short=x}}\n* [http://www.theoi.com/Potamos/PotamosAkheloios.html Theoi Project - Potamos Akheloios]\n* {{Cite NIE|wstitle=Achelous|year=1905 |short=x}}\n* Nicholas J. Molinari and Nicola Sisci:\n** [https://manfacedbulls.wordpress.com/ Bronze Coinage of the Man-Faced Bull]\n** [https://manfacedbullsar.wordpress.com/ Silver Coinage of the Man-Faced Bull]\n** [https://manfacedbullsau.wordpress.com/ Gold Coinage of the Man-Faced Bull]\n\n{{Greek mythology (deities)}}\n\n{{Subject bar |portal=Ancient Greece|portal2=Myths|commons =Achelous |s=Achelous}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Potamoi]]\n[[Category:Aetolian mythology]]\n[[Category:Achelous River]]\n[[Category:Characters in Greek mythology]]\n\n[[kk:\u0410\u0445\u0435\u043b\u043e\u0439 (\u0411\u0443\u0440\u0433\u0430\u0441 \u043e\u0431\u043b\u044b\u0441\u044b)]]\n", "name_user": "Arjayay", "label": "safe", "comment": "recieved > received", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Achelous"}
{"title_page": "Hossein Vafaei", "text_new": "{{short description|Iranian snooker player}}\n{{Infobox snooker player\n| name          = Hossein Vafaei \n| image         = \n| imagesize     = \n| caption       = \n| birth_date    = {{Birth date and age|1994|10|15|df=yes}}\n| birth_place   = [[Abadan, Iran|Abadan]], [[Iran]]\n| death_date    = \n| death_place   = \n| Sport country = {{IRI}}\n| Nickname      = The Prince of Persia\n| Professional  = 2012\u2013\n| High ranking  = 31 <small>(September 2019)</small>\n| Prize money   = [[Pound sterling|\u00a3]]276,162\n| High break    = '''146''': <br> <small>2019 China Open (qualifying)</small>\n| Century break = 41\n| Best finish   = ''Semi-final'' <small>([[2017 China Open (snooker)|2017 China Open]], [[2019 Welsh Open (snooker)|2019 Welsh Open]], [[2019 China Championship]])</small>\n| Ranking wins  = \n| Other wins    = \n| World champ   = \n| medals         =\n{{MedalCountry | {{IRI}} }}\n{{MedalSport | Men's [[Snooker]] }}\n{{MedalCompetition | [[Asian Indoor and Martial Arts Games]] }}\n{{MedalGold | [[2017 Asian Indoor and Martial Arts Games|2017 Ashgabat]] | [[Cue sports at the 2017 Asian Indoor and Martial Arts Games|Team]] }}\n{{MedalSilver | [[2017 Asian Indoor and Martial Arts Games|2017 Ashgabat]] | [[Cue sports at the 2017 Asian Indoor and Martial Arts Games|Singles]] }}\n}}\n\n'''Hossein Vafaei''' ({{lang-fa| \u062d\u0633\u06cc\u0646 \u0648\u0641\u0627\u06cc\u06cc \u0627\u06cc\u0648\u0631\u06cc}}, born October 15, 1994 in [[Abadan, Iran|Abadan]], [[Iran]]) is an [[Persian people|Iranian]] professional [[snooker]] player.<ref>{{cite web|title=VAFAEI AYOURI Hossein|url=http://www.gz2010.cn/info/ENG/ZB/ZBB101A_BS@@@@@@@@@@@@@@@ENG_number=224500.htm|publisher=[[Asian Games]]|accessdate=6 December 2011}}</ref> He was the first Iranian professional snooker player in the history of the game.<ref name=\"worldsnooker\">{{cite web|url=http://www.worldsnooker.com/page/NewsArticles/0,,13165~2724224,00.html |title=Hossein Set For Pro Tour |publisher=[[World Professional Billiards and Snooker Association|World Snooker]] |accessdate=19 May 2014 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140611132503/http://www.worldsnooker.com/page/NewsArticles/0%2C%2C13165~2724224%2C00.html |archivedate=11 June 2014 }}</ref> His attempts to travel to the [[United Kingdom]] to qualify for the major tournaments on the snooker calendar were denied due to [[Visa (document)|visa]] problems, but he gained a UK visa in February 2015.\n\n==Career==\n===2009/2010 season===\nHis first international tournament was the 2009 [[IBSF World Under-21 Snooker Championship|World Under-21 Amateur Snooker Championship]]. He reached the last 16 where he lost by five frames to three against [[Liu Chuang (snooker player)|Liu Chuang]].<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.cuesportsindia.com/global/2009/isbf/U21snooker.html | title=IBSF World Under-21 Snooker Championship 2009 | publisher=Cue Sports India | accessdate=19 May 2014}}</ref>\n\n===2010/2011 season===\nHe participated in the [[2010 Asian Games]] in [[Guangzhou]], [[China]] in the [[Cue sports at the 2010 Asian Games#Snooker singles|snooker singles competition]] and was beaten 4\u20131 by [[Dechawat Poomjaeng]] the last 16.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.cuesportsindia.com/global/2010/asiangames/AG2010SNK.html | title=Snooker (Men) Individual | publisher=Cue Sports India | accessdate=19 May 2014}}</ref> In December 2010, he played in the [[IBSF World Snooker Championship|World Amateur Snooker Championship]] and reached the last 16, where he lost 5\u20131 to [[Leo Fernandez]].<ref>{{cite web|title=World Snooker Championship 2010|url=http://ibsf.info/cgi-bin/ibsf.pl?A=ResultDetail&ID=21|publisher=[[International Billiards and Snooker Federation]]|accessdate=6 June 2013|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20101225053926/http://ibsf.info/cgi-bin/ibsf.pl?A=ResultDetail&ID=21|archivedate=25 December 2010}}</ref>\n\nIn April 2011, he reached the final of [[ACBS Asian Under-21 Snooker Championship]], but lost 7\u20133 to [[Cao Yupeng]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Asian Championship 2011 - 12th Under-21 Snooker|url=http://www.cuesportsindia.com/global/2011/acbs/U21snooker.htm|publisher=Cue Sports India|accessdate=6 December 2011}}</ref> Later in the month he participated in [[ACBS Asian Snooker Championship]], however, he could not advance past the group stage. He competed in Group C, and finished in fourth place with one win and three losses.<ref>[http://www.cuesportsindia.com/global/2011/acbs/snooker.htm 2011 Asian Snooker Championship]</ref>\n\n===2011/2012 season===\nIn September 2011, he received a wildcard to participate at the [[2011 Shanghai Masters|Shanghai Masters]], but could not advance to the first round as he lost 5\u20131 against [[Fergal O'Brien]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Shanghai Masters (2011)|url=http://www.snooker.org/res/index.asp?event=96|publisher=WWW Snooker|accessdate=24 July 2011}}</ref> In December, he won the [[IBSF World Snooker Championship|World Amateur Snooker Championship]] by defeating [[Lee Walker]] 10\u20139 in the final.<ref>{{cite web|title=Ayouri managed, retained the title in Asia|url=http://www.ibsf.info/cgi-bin/ibsf.pl?A=NewsDetail&ID=46|publisher=[[International Billiards and Snooker Federation]]|accessdate=5 December 2011|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120525065655/http://www.ibsf.info/cgi-bin/ibsf.pl?A=NewsDetail&ID=46|archivedate=25 May 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Results of 2011 IBSF World Men's Snooker Championship |url=http://www.ibsf.info/cgi-bin/ibsf.pl?A=ResultDetail&ID=27 |publisher=International Billiards and Snooker Federation |accessdate=5 December 2011 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130127140033/http://www.ibsf.info/cgi-bin/ibsf.pl?A=ResultDetail&ID=27 |archivedate=27 January 2013 }}</ref> He won the title at the age of 17 years and 81 days, which made him the youngest ever winner of the tournament, breaking [[Ian Preece|Ian Preece's]] record.<ref>{{cite web|last=Turner|first=Chris|title=Various Snooker Records|url=http://www.cajt.pwp.blueyonder.co.uk/Records.html|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130210111343/http://www.cajt.pwp.blueyonder.co.uk/Records.html|archivedate=10 February 2013|work=cajt.pwp.blueyonder.co.uk|publisher=Chris Turner's Snooker Archive|accessdate=6 December 2011}}</ref>\n\nVafaei received a wildcard to participate at the [[2012 World Open (snooker)|2012 World Open]],<ref>{{cite web|title=2012 Haikou World Open draw and format |url=http://www.worldsnooker.com/staticFiles/28/9a/0,,13165~170536,00.pdf |work=worldsnooker.com |publisher=[[World Professional Billiards and Snooker Association]] |accessdate=22 January 2012 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120131224354/http://www.worldsnooker.com/staticFiles/28/9a/0%2C%2C13165~170536%2C00.pdf |archivedate=31 January 2012 }}</ref> but lost 5\u20132 against [[Mark King (snooker player)|Mark King]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Haikou World Open (2012)|url=http://www.snooker.org/res/index.asp?event=105&season=2011|publisher=WWW Snooker|accessdate=4 March 2012}}</ref> In April 2012, he won [[ACBS Asian Under-21 Snooker Championship]], by defeating [[Zhang Anda]] 6\u20132 in the final.<ref>[http://www.cuesportsindia.com/global/2012/acbs/U21snooker.htm 13th  Asian Under-21 Snooker Championship 2012]</ref> He reached the semi-finals of [[ACBS Asian Snooker Championship]], where he lost 6\u20133 to [[Aditya Mehta]].<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.cuesportsindia.com/global/2012/acbs/snooker.htm | title=2012 Asian Snooker Championship | publisher=Cue Sports India | accessdate=19 May 2014}}</ref>\n\n===Attempt to turn professional===\nHe received a main snooker tour card courtesy of his World Amateur win to participate in the [[2012\u201313 snooker season|2012/2013]] and [[2013\u201314 snooker season|2013/2014]] seasons.<ref name=\"worldsnooker\" /><ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.worldsnooker.com/staticFiles/46/a4/0,,13165~173126,00.pdf | title=The Tour 2012/2013 Season Provisional Qualifying Criteria | publisher=[[World Professional Billiards and Snooker Association|World Snooker]] | accessdate=19 May 2014}}</ref> However, due to visa problems he could only participate in the [[2012 Six-red World Championship|Six-red World Championship]] in Thailand, where he lost in the last 16 to [[Judd Trump]], and [[Asian Players Tour Championship 2012/2013 \u2013 Event 2|APTC Event 2]] in China, where he lost to Li Yuan in the last 64.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://snooker.org/res/index.asp?player=666&season=2012 | title=Hossein Vafaei Ayouri 2012/2013 | publisher=Snooker.org | accessdate=3 June 2013}}</ref> It was a similar story in his second season as he only played in the [[Snooker at the World Games 2013 \u2013 men's singles|World Games]] (lost 3\u20130 to [[L\u00fc Haotian]] in the first round) and the [[2013 Six-red World Championship|Six-red World Championship]] (failed to advance beyond the group stage).<ref>{{cite web|title=Hossein Vafaei Ayouri 2013/2014|url=http://www.snooker.org/res/index.asp?season=2013&player=666|publisher=Snooker.org|accessdate=19 May 2014}}</ref>\n\n===2014 IBSF World Under-21s Championship===\nIn May 2014, Vafaei qualified as the top seed of his group at the [[IBSF World Under-21 Snooker Championship|2014 IBSF World Under-21 Snooker Championship]] by losing only one frame in the preliminary stage.<ref>[http://ibsfnews.com/index.php?option=com_k2&view=item&id=232:knockout-draw-for-world-under-21-snooker-championship&Itemid=181]</ref>\nHe then beat Poland's Mateusz Baranowski 7\u20133 in the semi-finals, compiling the first 147 in the history of the tournament in the process.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://ibsfnews.com/index.php?option=com_k2&view=item&id=239:hossein-hits-the-maximum&Itemid=181 | title=Hossein hits the maximum | publisher=[[International Billiards and Snooker Federation|IBSF]] | accessdate=19 May 2014}}</ref> He won the title by defeating Josh Boileau 8\u20133 in the final.<ref>{{cite web|last=Pathak|first=Vivek|title=Second world title for Hossein Vafaei|url=http://ibsfnews.com/index.php?option=com_k2&view=item&id=242:second-world-title-for-hossein-vafaei&Itemid=181|publisher=[[International Billiards and Snooker Federation]]|accessdate=18 May 2014|archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/6PfDivRiP?url=http://ibsfnews.com/index.php?option=com_k2&view=item&id=242:second-world-title-for-hossein-vafaei&Itemid=181|archivedate=18 May 2014|date=18 May 2014|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\n===Special dispensation for the 2014/15 season===\nIn June 2014, Vafaei received a special dispensation to compete on the Main Tour for the [[2014\u201315 snooker season|2014/15 season]].<ref name=\"Tirapongpaiboon-Ayouri\">{{cite web|title=Tirapongpaiboon/Ayouri Tour Cards|url=http://www.worldsnooker.com/page/NewsArticles/0,,13165~3910046,00.html|publisher=[[World Professional Billiards and Snooker Association]]|work=worldsnooker.com|accessdate=16 June 2014|date=16 June 2014}}</ref> In late February 2015, it was confirmed that Vafaei had gained a visa, leaving him able to enter the [[2015 World Snooker Championship]], where he lost 10\u20133 to [[Anthony McGill (snooker player)|Anthony McGill]] in the opening qualifying round.<ref>{{cite web|title=Visa For Vafaei|url=http://www.prosnookerblog.com/2015/02/26/visa-for-vafaei/|publisher=Pro Snooker Blog|work=prosnookerblog.com|accessdate=3 March 2015|date=26 February 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web | url=http://snooker.org/res/index.asp?player=666 | title=Hossein Vafaei Ayouri 2014/2015 | publisher=Snooker.org | accessdate=8 April 2015}}</ref>\n\n===2015/2016 season===\nThe [[2015 Australian Goldfields Open]] was the first ranking event of the [[2015\u201316 snooker season|2015/2016 season]] and Vafaei qualified for it by beating Charlie Walters 5\u20133, [[Zak Surety]] 5\u20133, [[Lee Walker]] 5\u20134 and [[Dominic Dale]] 5\u20133. In his debut at the venue stage of a ranking event, Vafaei played [[Michael White (snooker player)|Michael White]] in the opening round where he lost 5\u20133.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.worldsnooker.com/ayouri-into-final-round/ | title=Hotshot Hossein Is Bendigo Bound | publisher=[[World Professional Billiards and Snooker Association|World Snooker]] | accessdate=6 June 2015}}</ref> He played in the [[2015 UK Championship (snooker)|UK Championship]] for the first time (losing 6\u20131 to [[Luca Brecel]] in the first round) and the [[2016 Welsh Open (snooker)|Welsh Open]] (losing 4\u20132 to [[Robin Hull]] in the first round).<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.snooker.org/res/index.asp?player=666&season=2015 | title=Hossein Vafaei Ayouri 2015/2016 | publisher=Snooker.org | accessdate=20 March 2016}}</ref>\n\n===2016/2017 season===\nVafaei enjoyed wins over [[Rod Lawler]], [[Zak Surety]], [[Sanderson Lam]] and [[Scott Donaldson]] at the [[2016 Northern Ireland Open|Northern Ireland Open]] to reach his first ranking event quarter-final, where he lost 5\u20133 to [[Mark King (snooker player)|Mark King]].<ref>{{cite news | url=http://www.tehrantimes.com/news/408397/Iran-s-Hossein-Vafaei-makes-history-in-Northern-Ireland-Open| title=Iran\u2019s Hossein Vafaei makes history in Northern Ireland Open| newspaper=[[Tehran Times]]| accessdate=19 February 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.romfordrecorder.co.uk/sport/dreadful_king_into_northern_ireland_open_last_four_1_4783616| title=\u2018Dreadful\u2019 King into Northern Ireland Open last four| publisher=[[Romford Recorder]]| accessdate=19 February 2017}}</ref> He also had a good run at the [[2017 Welsh Open (snooker)|Welsh Open]] as he beat Lam, [[Christopher Keogan]] and [[Ali Carter]] to advance to the fourth round and he was defeated 4\u20131 by [[Judd Trump]].<ref name=\"2016/17\">{{cite web | url=http://www.snooker.org/res/index.asp?player=666&season=2016| title=Hossein Vafaei Ayouri 2016/2017| publisher=Snooker.org | accessdate=19 February 2017}}</ref> A month after the Welsh Open, Vafaei also had a good run of form at the [[2017 China Open (snooker)|China Open]], defeating [[Joe Perry (snooker player)|Joe Perry]] 5\u20132, [[Ben Woollaston]] 5\u20134 and [[Rory McLeod (snooker player)|Rory McLeod]] 5\u20133. This booked him a place in the second ranking event quarter-final of his career within the space of a few months. His opponent was to be [[Judd Trump]] and Vafaei (the world number 74) was able to keep the world number two at bay and win by 5\u20133.<ref>{{citeweb|url= https://www.bbc.com/sport/snooker/39458623|title=China Open snooker: Judd Trump loses to Iranian world number 76 Hossein Vafaei|date=31 March 2017|work=BBC Sport|accessdate=6 April 2017}}</ref> He lost his first semi-final 6\u20131 to [[Mark Williams (snooker player)|Mark Williams]].<ref>{{citeweb|url= https://www.bbc.com/sport/snooker/39466158|title=China Open: Mark Williams to face Mark Selby in final|date=1 April 2017|work=BBC Sport|accessdate=6 April 2017}}</ref> After overcoming [[Hatem Yassen]] 10\u20131 and [[Matthew Selt]] 10\u20136, Vafaei was one win away from qualifying for the [[2017 World Snooker Championship|World Championship]], but narrowly lost 10\u20138 to [[Tom Ford (snooker player)|Tom Ford]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.worldsnooker.com/obrien-wins-record-two-hour-frame/|title=O'Brien Wins Record Two-Hour Frame|publisher=[[World Professional Billiards and Snooker Association|World Snooker]]|accessdate=14 April 2017}}</ref> He finished the campaign inside the top 64 in the world rankings and retained his place on the tour.<ref>{{cite web|title=Rankings 2016/2017|url=http://www.snooker.org/res/index.asp?season=2016&template=31|publisher=Snooker.org|accessdate=7 May 2017}}</ref>\n\n==Performance and rankings timeline==\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"font-size:85%;\"\n|- bgcolor=\"#efefef\"\n! '''Tournament'''\n! [[2011\u201312 snooker season|2011/<br/>12]]\n! [[2012\u201313 snooker season|2012/<br/>13]]\n! [[2013\u201314 snooker season|2013/<br/>14]]\n! [[2014\u201315 snooker season|2014/<br/>15]]\n! [[2015\u201316 snooker season|2015/<br/>16]]\n! [[2016\u201317 snooker season|2016/<br/>17]]\n! [[2017\u201318 snooker season|2017/<br/>18]]\n! [[2018\u201319 snooker season|2018/<br/>19]]\n! [[2019\u201320 snooker season|2019/<br/>20]]\n|-\n| style=\"background:#EFEFEF;\" | [[Snooker world rankings|Ranking]]<ref name=\"Ranking history\">{{cite web|title=Ranking History|url=http://www.snooker.org/rnk/history.asp|publisher=Snooker.org|accessdate=6 February 2011}}</ref><ref group=\"nb\">It shows the ranking at the beginning of the season.</ref> \n| align=\"center\" |<ref group=\"nb\" name=\"AMA\">He was an amateur.</ref>\n| align=\"center\" |<ref group=\"nb\" name=\"UR\">New players on the Main Tour don't have a ranking.</ref>\n| align=\"center\" |[[Snooker world rankings 2013/2014|97]]\n| align=\"center\" |<ref group=\"nb\" name=\"SD\">Players qualified through special dispensation started the season without prize money ranking points.</ref>\n| align=\"center\" |[[Snooker world rankings 2015/2016|126]]\n| align=\"center\" |[[Snooker world rankings 2016/2017|89]]\n| align=\"center\" |[[Snooker world rankings 2017/2018|59]]\n| align=\"center\" |[[Snooker world rankings 2018/2019|45]]\n| align=\"center\" |[[Snooker world rankings 2019/2020|40]]\n|-\n| colspan=\"10\" | '''Ranking tournaments'''\n|-\n|style=\"background:#EFEFEF;\"| [[Riga Masters (snooker)|Riga Masters]]<ref group=\"nb\">The event was called the Riga Open (2014/2015\u20132015/2016)</ref>\n|colspan=\"3\" style=\"text-align:center; color:#cccccc;\"| Not Held\n|colspan=\"2\" style=\"text-align:center; color:#cccccc;\"| MR\n|align=\"center\" style=\"color:#cccccc;\"|WD\n|align=\"center\" style=\"background:#afeeee;\"|[[2017 Riga Masters|2R]]\n|align=\"center\" style=\"color:#cccccc;\"|A\n|align=\"center\" style=\"color:#cccccc;\"|WD\n|-\n|style=\"background:#EFEFEF;\" | {{nowrap|[[International Championship]]}} \n|a