olspan=\"20\" style=\"color:#cccccc;\"|Tournament Not Held\n|-\n|style=\"background:#EFEFEF;\" | [[2011 Hainan Classic|Hainan Classic]]\n|colspan=\"2\" style=\"text-align:center; color:#ccc;\"|Not Held\n| style=\"text-align:center; background:#afeeee;\"|[[2011 Hainan Classic|RR]]\n|colspan=\"30\" style=\"text-align:center; color:#ccc;\"|Tournament Not Held\n|}\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"font-size:78%;\"\n|- bgcolor=\"#efefef\"\n! colspan=\"6\"|Performance Table Legend\n|-\n| align=\"center\" style=\"color:#cccccc;\" width=\"30\"|LQ\n| lost in the qualifying draw\n| align=\"center\" style=\"background:#afeeee;\"|#R\n| lost in the early rounds of the tournament<br />(WR = Wildcard round, RR = Round robin)\n| align=\"center\" style=\"background:#ffebcd;\"|QF\n| lost in the quarter-finals\n|-\n| align=\"center\" style=\"background:yellow;\"|SF\n| lost in the semi-finals\n| align=\"center\" style=\"background:#D8BFD8;\"|F\n| lost in the final\n| align=\"center\" style=\"background:#00ff00;\"|'''W'''\n| won the tournament\n|-\n| align=\"center\" style=\"color:#cccccc;\" width=\"30\"|DNQ\n| did not qualify for the tournament\n| align=\"center\" style=\"color:#cccccc;\" width=\"30\"|A\n| did not participate in the tournament\n| align=\"center\" style=\"color:#cccccc;\" width=\"30\"|WD\n| withdrew from the tournament\n|}\n{|class=\"wikitable\" style=\"font-size:90%\"\n|-\n|  style=\"text-align:center; color:#ccc;\" colspan=\"4\"|NH / Not Held || means an event was not held.\n|-\n|  style=\"text-align:center; color:#ccc;\" colspan=\"4\"|NR / Non-Ranking Event || means an event is/was no longer a ranking event.\n|-\n|  style=\"text-align:center; color:#ccc;\" colspan=\"4\"|R / Ranking Event || means an event is/was a ranking event.\n|-\n|  style=\"text-align:center; color:#ccc;\" colspan=\"4\"|MR / Minor-Ranking Event || means an event is/was a minor-ranking event.\n|}\n{{reflist|group=\"nb\"}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|2}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category|Li Yan}}\n* [http://prosnookerblog.com/players/i-l/li-yan/ Pro Snooker Blog Profile]\n*\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Li, Yan}}\n[[Category:1992 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Chinese snooker players]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Chinese snooker player}}\n{{Blacklisted-links|1=\n*http://prosnookerblog.com/players/i-l/li-yan/\n*:''Triggered by <code>\\bprosnookerblog\\.com\\b</code> on the local blacklist''\n*http://www.cuetracker.net/pages/players.php?ID=39\n*:''Triggered by <code>\\bcuetracker\\.net\\b</code> on the local blacklist''|bot=Cyberbot II|invisible=false}}\n{{Chinese name|[[Li (surname)|Li]]}}\n{{Infobox snooker player\n| name          = Li Yan\n| image         = Li Yan PHC 2012-1.jpg\n| caption       = Li Yan at the [[European Tour 2012/2013 \u2013 Event 1|2012 Paul Hunter Classic]]\n| birth_date    = {{birth date and age|1992|09|17}}\n| birth_place   = [[China]]\n| Sport country = {{CHN}}\n| Nickname      = \n| Professional  = 2011\u20132014\n| High ranking  = 64 <small>(January\u2013February 2012)</small><ref>{{cite web|title=Issued after the Players Tour Championship 2012 \u2013 Event 12 |date=9 January 2012 |url=http://www.worldsnooker.com/staticFiles/ad/98/0,,13165~170157,00.pdf |work=World Snooker |publisher=[[World Professional Billiards and Snooker Association]] | format=PDF |accessdate=1 January 2013 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/68QZnaiok?url=http://www.worldsnooker.com/staticFiles/ad/98/0%2C%2C13165~170157%2C00.pdf |archivedate=15 June 2012 }}</ref>\n| Prize money   = [[Pound sterling|\u00a3]]39,132<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.snookerdatabase.co.uk/PlayerDetails.aspx?playerKey=208| title=Li Yan Player Profile | publisher=Snooker Database| accessdate=26 October 2015}}</ref>\n| High break    = 132 <small>([[Players Tour Championship 2011/2012 \u2013 Event 3|2011 PTC3]])</small>\n| Century break = 8<ref>{{cite web|title=Li Yan|url=http://www.cuetracker.net/pages/players.php?ID=39|publisher=CueTracker \u2013 Snooker Database|accessdate=26 October 2015}}</ref>\n| Best finish   = Last 32 <small>([[2009 Shanghai Masters]], [[2011 UK Championship (snooker)|2011 UK Championship]], [[2013 Indian Open]])</small>\n| Ranking wins  = \n| Other wins    = \n| World champ   = \n}}\n\n'''Li Yan''' (born September 17, 1992) is a former professional [[snooker]] player from the [[People's Republic of China]].\n\n==Career==\n\n===Early career===\nLi received a wild card for the [[2008 Shanghai Masters]], losing 1-5 to [[Anthony Hamilton (snooker player)|Anthony Hamilton]]. At the [[2009 Shanghai Masters]], he defeated [[Gerard Greene]] 5-4, before losing to [[Ryan Day (snooker player)|Ryan Day]] in the last 32.\n\n===2011/2012 season===\nLi qualified for the [[Snooker season 2011/2012|2011/2012]] professional Main Tour as one of four semi-finalists from the second Q School event.<ref>{{cite web|title=Chinese Duo Join Main Tour|url=http://www.worldsnooker.com/page/NewsArticles/0,,13165~2364573,00.html|work=worldsnooker.com|publisher=[[World Professional Billiards and Snooker Association]]|accessdate=22 May 2011}}</ref> As a new player on the tour Li would need to win four matches in order to reach the main stage of the ranking tournaments. He accomplished this in qualifying for the second biggest tournament on the snooker calendar, the [[2011 UK Championship (snooker)|UK Championship]], with wins over Stuart Carrington, [[Andy Hicks]], [[Jack Lisowski]] and [[Fergal O'Brien]].<ref>{{cite web | url=http://snooker.org/res/index.asp?player=296&season=2011 | title=Li Yan 2011/2012 | publisher=Snooker.org | accessdate=10 May 2012}}</ref> He faced former world champion [[Shaun Murphy (snooker player)|Shaun Murphy]] in the first round of the event and was beaten 3\u20136.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.yorkpress.co.uk/sport/9401279.UK_Snooker_Championship__Martin_Gould_and_Shaun_Murphy_into_round_two/ | title=Martin Gould and Shaun Murphy into round two | accessdate=December 12, 2011}}</ref> He could not qualify for another tournament for the remainder of the season but did play in all 12 of the [[Players Tour Championship 2011/2012|PTC]] events throughout the season reaching, but not progressing past, the last 16 on three occasions.<ref name=\"OOM\">{{cite web|url=http://snooker.org/res/index.asp?template=10&season=2011|title=Order of Merit|publisher=WWW Snooker|date=8 January 2012|accessdate=31 March 2012}}</ref>\n\nLi finished the season ranked world number 67, just outside the top 64 who retain their places on the tour.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.worldsnooker.com/staticFiles/1d/b0/0,,13165~176157,00.pdf |title=Official World Ranking List for the 2012/2013 Season |accessdate=10 May 2012 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/69tDLWozD?url=http://www.worldsnooker.com/staticFiles/1d/b0/0%2C%2C13165~176157%2C00.pdf |archivedate=13 August 2012 }}</ref> However, due to being ranked 43rd on the PTC [[Players Tour Championship 2011/2012#Order of Merit|Order of Merit]] he secured one of the eight spots for the highest non-qualified players to play in the [[Snooker season 2012/2013|2012/2013 season]].<ref name=\"OOM\"/>\n\n===2012/2013 season===\nLi only won two matches in ranking event qualifiers in the 2012/2013 season.<ref name=\"2012/13\">{{cite web | url=http://snooker.org/res/index.asp?player=296&season=2012 | title=Li Yan 2012/2013 | publisher=Snooker.org | accessdate=11 April 2013}}</ref> His best results in the minor-ranking [[Players Tour Championship 2012/2013|Players Tour Championship]] events were last 16 losses in the third [[Asian Players Tour Championship 2012/2013 \u2013 Event 3|Asian PTC]] and the fourth [[European Tour 2012/2013 \u2013 Event 4|European Tour Event]], to [[Stuart Bingham]] and [[Rory McLeod (snooker player)|Rory McLeod]] respectively.<ref name=\"2012/13\"/> He lost seven consecutive games after this, before beating [[Robbie Williams (snooker player)|Robbie Williams]] 10\u20137 in the first round of [[2013 World Snooker Championship#Qualifying|World Championship Qualifying]], but his season was ended when he lost 10\u20132 to [[Jimmy Robertson (snooker player)|Jimmy Robertson]] in the following round.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://snooker.org/res/index.asp?event=225 | title=Betfair World Championship Qualifiers | publisher=Snooker.org | accessdate=11 April 2013}}</ref> Li dropped 17 places in the rankings during the year to finish it at world number 84.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.worldsnooker.com/staticFiles/49/bc/0,,13165~179273,00.pdf |title=Official World Snooker Ranking List For The 2013/2014 Season |publisher=[[World Professional Billiards and Snooker Association|World Snooker]] |accessdate=24 May 2013 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130611202605/http://www.worldsnooker.com/staticFiles/49/bc/0%2C%2C13165~179273%2C00.pdf |archivedate=11 June 2013 }}</ref>\n\n===2013/2014 season===\nThe first ranking tournament Li could qualify for in the [[Snooker season 2013/2014|2013/2014 season]] was the [[2013 Indian Open|Indian Open]] by beating [[Peter Lines]] 4\u20132. He then edged out [[Jeff Cundy]] 4\u20133 to record his first ever win in the main draw of a ranking event, before being thrashed 4\u20130 by [[John Higgins (snooker player)|John Higgins]].<ref name=\"2013/14\">{{cite web|title=Li Yan 2013/2014|url=http://www.snooker.org/res/index.asp?season=2013&player=296|publisher=Snooker.org|accessdate=4 May 2014}}</ref> Li also qualified for the [[2013 International Championship|International Championship]] and [[2014 World Open (snooker)|World Open]] during the season, losing to compatriots [[Liang Wenbo]] and [[Ding Junhui]] in the first round.<ref name=\"2013/14\"/> He won more than one match in an event for the only time this season in the [[2014 World Snooker Championship|World Championship]] qualifiers by defeating Elliot Slessor 10\u20135, [[Dave Harold]] 10\u20133 and [[Joe Swail]] 10\u20138, to be just one win away from reaching [[World Snooker Championship|The Crucible]] for the first time, but he was thoroughly outplayed by [[Xiao Guodong]] in a 10\u20131 loss.<ref>{{cite web | url=https://uk.eurosport.yahoo.com/news/snooker-ebdon-fails-reach-world-championship-213353682--spt.html | title=Snooker - Ebdon fails to reach World Championship | publisher=[[Eurosport]] | accessdate=4 May 2014}}</ref> The result ensured Li would not be among the top 64 in the world rankings who keep their places on the snooker tour as he was ranked number 86 and so he played in [[World Snooker Tour#Q School|Q School]] in an attempt to earn his place back.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.worldsnooker.com/staticFiles/71/c1/0,,13165~180593,00.pdf |title=World Snooker Rankings After the 2014 World Championship |publisher=[[World Professional Billiards and Snooker Association|World Snooker]] |accessdate=9 May 2014 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140508030740/http://www.worldsnooker.com/staticFiles/71/c1/0%2C%2C13165~180593%2C00.pdf |archivedate= 8 May 2014 }}</ref> Li lost in the last 128 of the first event and the last 32 of the second to confirm his exit from the tour.<ref name=\"2013/14\"/>\n\n===2014/2015 season===\nLi entered the three [[Players Tour Championship 2014/2015|Asian Tour]] events during the [[Snooker season 2014/2015|2014/2015 season]], but was knocked out in the first round of each. He again entered Q School, but could not win a match in either of the events, losing 4\u20133 to both [[Daniel Wells (snooker player)|Daniel Wells]] and Jamie Rhys Clarke.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://snooker.org/res/index.asp?player=296&season=2014 | title=Li Yan 2014/2015 | publisher=Snooker.org | accessdate=10 May 2015}}</ref>\n\n===2015/2016 season===\nLi only played in the [[Asian Tour 2015/2016 \u2013 Event 1|Haining Open]] and was eliminated 4\u20131 in the first round by [[John Higgins (snooker player)|John Higgins]].<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.snooker.org/res/index.asp?player=296&season=2015 | title=Li Yan 2015/2016 | publisher=Snooker.org | accessdate=26 September 2016}}</ref>\n\n==Performance and rankings timeline==\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"  style=\"font-size:85%;\"\n|- style=\"background:#efefef;\"\n! '''Tournament''' \n! [[Snooker season 2008/2009|2008/<br />09]]\n! [[Snooker season 2009/2010|2009/<br />10]]\n! [[Snooker season 2010/2011|2010/<br />11]]\n! [[Snooker season 2011/2012|2011/<br />12]]\n! [[Snooker season 2012/2013|2012/<br />13]]\n! [[Snooker season 2013/2014|2013/<br />14]]\n! [[Snooker season 2014/2015|2014/<br />15]]\n! [[Snooker season 2016/2017|2016/<br />17]]\n! [[Snooker season 2017/2018|2017/<br />18]]\n! [[Snooker season 2018/2019|2018/<br />19]]\n! [[Snooker season 2019/2020|2019/<br />20]]\n|-\n| style=\"background:#EFEFEF;\"|[[Snooker world rankings|Ranking]]<ref name=\"Ranking history\">{{cite web|title=Ranking History|url=http://www.snooker.org/rnk/history.asp|publisher=Snooker.org|accessdate=6 February 2011}}</ref><ref group=\"nb\">From the 2010/2011 season it shows the ranking at the beginning of the season.</ref>\n| align=\"center\" |<ref group=\"nb\" name=\"AMA\">He was an amateur.</ref>\n| align=\"center\" |<ref group=\"nb\" name=\"AMA\">He was an amateur.</ref>\n| align=\"center\" |<ref group=\"nb\" name=\"AMA\">He was an amateur.</ref>\n| align=\"center\" |<ref group=\"nb\" name=\"UR\">New players on the Main Tour don't have a ranking.</ref>\n| align=\"center\" |<ref group=\"nb\" name=\"PTC\">Players qualified through Players Tour Championship Order of Merit started the season without ranking points.</ref>\n| align=\"center\" |[[Snooker world rankings 2013/2014|84]]\n| align=\"center\" |<ref group=\"nb\" name=\"AMA\">He was an amateur.</ref>\n| align=\"center\" |<ref group=\"nb\" name=\"AMA\">He was an amateur.</ref>\n| align=\"center\" |<ref group=\"nb\" name=\"AMA\">He was an amateur.</ref>\n| align=\"center\" |<ref group=\"nb\" name=\"AMA\">He was an amateur.</ref>\n| align=\"center\" |<ref group=\"nb\"